    questions: [
    { questionText: "What is the Nine-Point Code of Conduct given by Bhagawan?", options: ["Daily meditation, group bhajan, Ceiling on Desires, reading Sai literature, attending Seva and practising human values", "Attending bhajans daily and weekly fasting", "Morning yoga, evening prayers and vegetarianism", "Annual pilgrimage, daily japa and silence days"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "The Nine-Point Code of Conduct covers daily spiritual practices, service, group activities, and values-based living — a practical guideline for all Sai devotees.", valueTag: 'Right Conduct', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What is the Ceiling on Desires programme?", options: ["Limiting waste in food, money, time and energy and donating savings for service", "Fasting on certain days of the month", "Wearing simple clothing always", "Avoiding all luxury in travel and accommodation"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "'Ceiling on Desires' (COD): limit unnecessary consumption. Savings in food, money, time and energy are channelled into welfare activities — connecting dharma with practical economics.", valueTag: 'Right Conduct', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What is Jyoti (Treat) meditation taught by Bhagawan?", options: ["Visualising divine flame expanding from one's heart to illuminate the world", "Focusing only on breathing", "Chanting Gayatri for one hour", "Staring at a physical flame on an altar"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Jyoti meditation: visualise a flame in the heart, expand it to the body, room, community, nation, and universe — experiencing unity with all creation in divine light.", valueTag: 'Peace', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan say about vegetarianism?", options: ["Sattvic food supports spiritual growth by reducing tamas and rajas", "It is mandatory for all devotees", "It only applies to initiated devotees", "It has no direct spiritual relevance"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan taught that sattvic (pure) food — vegetarian, lightly spiced, freshly prepared — reduces agitation (rajas) and inertia (tamas), supporting spiritual clarity and sadhana.", valueTag: 'Non-violence', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What is the practice of Seva (service) according to Bhagawan?", options: ["Serving others as serving God — without expectation of reward or recognition", "A religious duty performed only on festival days", "A way to earn individual good karma", "An activity only for organisation members"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan: 'When you serve others, you are serving God.' Seva must be selfless, without desire for recognition — it transforms the server as much as the person served.", valueTag: 'Love', difficulty: 'Seeker' },
    { questionText: "What is the purpose of group bhajans in Sai teaching?", options: ["To create a collective divine vibration purifying the environment", "Social gathering for Sai devotees", "Satisfying traditional temple rituals", "Practising musical skills"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Group singing of God's names creates a powerful collective vibration that purifies the atmosphere of a home or community. Bhagawan said bhajans can shower rain and restore peace.", valueTag: 'Peace', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What did Bhagawan say about the importance of silence (mouna)?", options: ["Observe mouna daily — it conserves energy and allows God's voice to be heard", "It is only for advanced yogis", "Practise only on Shivaratri", "Complete silence is not necessary — just speak softly"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan taught that mouna (silence) conserves prana (life force) and clears inner noise, making space for the divine voice. 'Speak only what is true, necessary and kind.'", valueTag: 'Peace', difficulty: 'Master' },
    { questionText: "What is the Sai approach to integrating Bhakti, Jnana and Karma?", options: ["All three must be integrated — devotion, wisdom and righteous action together", "Only bhakti is needed", "Jnana alone leads to liberation", "Karma yoga is for householders only"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan taught the integration of Bhakti (loving devotion), Jnana (self-knowledge), and Karma (righteous service) — none alone is complete without the others.", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Master' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan teach about early morning spiritual practice?", options: ["Rise before sunrise, pray, and begin the day with God consciousness", "Rise at any time if spiritually inclined", "Morning practice is only for elderly devotees", "Any time of day is equally suitable"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan strongly recommended the Brahma Muhurta (period before sunrise) for prayer and meditation — the atmosphere is most sattvic and the mind most receptive to divine presence.", valueTag: 'Right Conduct', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What food practices does Bhagawan recommend for spiritual aspirants?", options: ["Sattvic, vegetarian, simple food eaten in moderation with gratitude", "Fast completely on all festival days", "Eat only once a day", "Follow a strict raw food diet"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan prescribed sattvic food (vegetarian, fresh, lightly prepared) in moderate quantities, eaten mindfully with gratitude — not as indulgence but as fuel for the divine instrument.", valueTag: 'Non-violence', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "How does Bhagawan describe the daily Sai spiritual routine?", options: ["Wake up with God, spend the day with God, go to sleep with God", "Attend formal rituals three times daily", "Spend two hours in temple daily", "Meditate for four hours every morning"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan's prescription: Wake up thinking of God; remember God during all activities; go to sleep with God in mind. Transform all of daily life into continuous worship.", valueTag: 'Right Conduct', difficulty: 'Seeker' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan say about managing anger?", options: ["Face it, trace it to the root cause and erase it through understanding", "Express it openly to clear the air", "Suppress it through will power", "Channel it into productive activity"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan said about anger: 'Face it — acknowledge it. Trace it — find the ego-attachment at its root. Erase it — through wisdom, love, and realisation of our divine nature.'", valueTag: 'Right Conduct', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What is the correct attitude towards one's work according to Bhagawan?", options: ["Offer all work to God — see it as worship, not mere livelihood", "Work only for spiritual activities", "Minimise worldly responsibilities", "Work hard to earn enough for religious activities"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan taught: 'Work is worship. Duty is God.' Every action — cooking, farming, teaching — becomes sacred when performed as an offering to the divine with love and excellence.", valueTag: 'Right Conduct', difficulty: 'Seeker' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan say about the relationship between breath and God?", options: ["Each inhalation is 'So' (He) and each exhalation is 'Ham' (I) — So'ham — I am He", "Breath has no spiritual significance", "Only pranayama breathing is spiritual", "Breath control leads to samadhi automatically"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Every breath is a natural mantra: inhalation ('So' = That/God) and exhalation ('Ham' = I/Self). So'ham — the primordial mantra of realisation breathed 21,600 times daily by every being.", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Master' },
    { questionText: "What is Bhagawan's teaching on controlling the mind?", options: ["The mind is a monkey — train it with practice and detachment, one thought at a time", "The mind cannot be controlled", "Control the mind through strict fasting", "Use drugs or herbs to quieten the mind"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan compared the mind to a drunken monkey stung by a scorpion. The remedy: Namasmarana, sattvic food, good company (satsang), and consistent meditation practice.", valueTag: 'Peace', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan teach about the function of dreams during sadhana?", options: ["Dreams can carry divine messages — purify the subconscious through sadhana to receive them clearly", "Dreams are meaningless random images", "Dreams are only past memories being processed", "Dreams should be ignored entirely by spiritual aspirants"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan appeared to countless devotees in dreams — guiding, warning, comforting. He taught that a purified mind through sadhana becomes capable of receiving divine communication even in sleep.", valueTag: 'Peace', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What is the Sai teaching on controlling speech (Vak Shuddhi)?", options: ["Speak only what is sweet, true, and useful — never gossip, slander or flatter falsely", "Silence is always better than speaking", "Speak freely but with good intentions", "Only saints need to control speech"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan's formula for speech: Is it True? Is it Kind? Is it Necessary? If a statement fails any of these, it is better left unspoken. Speech purification (Vak Shuddhi) purifies the entire being.", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan say about pilgrimage and visiting temples?", options: ["Inner purity matters more than external pilgrimage — the heart is the true temple", "Physical pilgrimage is essential for all devotees", "Temple visits replace the need for daily practice", "The more pilgrimages, the more merit accumulated"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan: 'You need not go on pilgrimage to find God. God is in your heart. Clean the temple of your heart first — then you will find God wherever you look.'", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "How does Bhagawan recommend one deal with fear?", options: ["Surrender to God completely — fear arises from attachment to the body and ego", "Avoid all fearful situations", "Courage comes from physical strength", "Ignore fear and act despite it"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan: 'Fear comes from attachment (to body, to possessions, to relationships). Surrender to God and the eternal Atma that cannot be harmed, and fear dissolves automatically.'", valueTag: 'Peace', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan say is the purpose of human birth?", options: ["To realise our divine nature and return to merger with God — not to repeat worldly cycles", "To accumulate good karma for next birth", "To fulfil worldly duties and then rest", "To worship God in temples daily"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan: 'Human birth is the rarest and most precious of all births — it alone grants the capacity for Self-realisation. Do not waste it on purely worldly pursuits.' The goal is liberation.", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Master' },
    ]
