    questions: [
    { questionText: "What did Bhagawan declare as the purpose of His Avatar?", options: ["To foster all mankind with bliss and lead the strayed back to righteousness", "To build temples and institutions", "To perform miracles for the faithful", "To establish a new religion"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "From His 1947 letter: 'I have a task — to foster all mankind with bliss. I have a vow — to lead all who stray away from the straight path again into goodness and save them.'", valueTag: 'Love', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan mean by 'God is Love, Love is God'?", options: ["God's essential nature is Love — to love unconditionally is to know God", "It is a philosophical equation only", "This refers only to divine scripture", "Human love and divine love are completely different"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "God's fundamental quality is unconditional love. When humans love unconditionally — without expectation or selfishness — they express their divine nature and draw close to God.", valueTag: 'Love', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan teach about the nature of the Atma?", options: ["The Atma is eternal, pure, omniscient — beyond birth and death", "The Atma dies with the body", "The Atma is only in holy people", "The Atma is separate from God forever"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "The Atma (individual soul) is a spark of the universal Brahman — pure, eternal, unchanging, omnipresent. Realising this identity is the highest goal of human life.", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What is the Sai teaching on 'Unity of Faiths'?", options: ["All religions are like rivers — different paths to the same ocean of God", "Only one religion is fully true", "Religions should all merge into one", "Religion is a personal matter with no common ground"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan: 'There is only one religion — the Religion of Love. There is only one God — He is omnipresent.' All faiths point to the same divine truth when understood in their depth.", valueTag: 'Love', difficulty: 'Seeker' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan say is the highest form of intelligence?", options: ["Discrimination (Viveka) — the capacity to distinguish the real from the unreal", "Memory and recall", "Logical reasoning", "Scientific thinking"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Viveka (discrimination) — the capacity to discern the permanent (Atma/God) from the impermanent (body/world) — is the highest human faculty according to Bhagawan.", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Master' },
    { questionText: "What is the Brahmastra (ultimate weapon) that Bhagawan gives devotees?", options: ["The Name of God (Namasmarana) — it protects in all circumstances", "Physical armour and protection", "Medical science for the body", "Legal rights and knowledge"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan said: 'Namasmarana (remembrance of God's Name) is the Brahmastra — the most powerful protection in all ages. It purifies, protects, and ultimately liberates.'", valueTag: 'Peace', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What is the Sai teaching on death?", options: ["Death is a doorway, not an end — the Atma continues its journey toward God", "Death is the final end of all experience", "Only good people survive death", "Death brings rebirth into the same family"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan: 'Death is not the end — it is a change of garment. The Atma, eternal and undying, continues its journey. For devoted ones, death is graduation into God's embrace.'", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "According to Bhagawan, what distinguishes a human from animals?", options: ["The capacity to seek God and realise one's divine nature", "Intelligence and reason", "Emotional complexity", "Language and communication"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan: 'Animals eat, sleep, fear and reproduce — and so do humans. What distinguishes human beings is Viveka (discrimination), Vairagya (detachment) and the capacity for God-realisation.'", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan say about the power of positive company (Satsang)?", options: ["Good company elevates consciousness and accelerates spiritual progress", "Social status determines spiritual growth", "Company has no effect on spiritual progress", "Only solitary practice leads to realisation"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan strongly recommended Satsang (good company): 'Tell me your company and I will tell you what you are.' Good company influences thoughts, which shape character, which determines destiny.", valueTag: 'Right Conduct', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What is Bhagawan's teaching on the relationship between love and liberation?", options: ["Pure love for God naturally dissolves the ego and leads to liberation", "Liberation requires decades of harsh austerity", "Only jnana (intellectual knowledge) leads to liberation", "Liberation is predestined and cannot be earned"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan: 'Love is the royal road to liberation. When you love God completely, the ego — the only barrier to liberation — melts away in the fire of divine love.' Bhakti leads to Mukti.", valueTag: 'Love', difficulty: 'Master' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan say about the meaning of 'Sai'?", options: ["Sai means Divine Mother in the Persian tradition — Sai Baba means Divine Mother/Father", "Sai is a name with no specific meaning", "Sai refers to a geographical location", "Sai is derived from Sanskrit only"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "'Sai' comes from Persian meaning 'Divine Mother' and 'Baba' means Father. Shirdi Baba first bore this name, and Bhagawan confirmed His identity as the same divine being in a new form.", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What is the spiritual significance of Bhagawan's name 'Bhagawan'?", options: ["Bhagawan means one who possesses all six divine qualities: sovereignty, righteousness, fame, prosperity, wisdom and detachment", "It is an honorific title given by devotees", "It means 'the holy one' in Sanskrit", "It is a name given at birth"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan = one who possesses all six divine qualities (Bhaga): Aishwarya (sovereignty), Dharma (righteousness), Yashas (fame), Shri (prosperity), Jnana (wisdom), Vairagya (detachment).", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Master' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan say about karma?", options: ["Karma is the law of cause and effect — every action returns its fruit; surrender to God transcends karma", "Karma can only be resolved by suffering", "Karma is fatalistic — nothing can change it", "Karma only affects the physical body"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan: 'Karma is real — as you sow, so shall you reap. But divine grace (prasada) can mitigate karma. Surrender to God dissolves the karmic burden through His infinite love.'", valueTag: 'Right Conduct', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What is Bhagawan's teaching about non-attachment to results (Nishkama Karma)?", options: ["Act with full effort but surrender results to God without craving or aversion", "Work as little as possible to avoid karma", "Only renunciants can be truly non-attached", "Non-attachment means not caring about quality of work"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Nishkama Karma (desireless action) — from the Bhagavad Gita — means: Do your duty with full dedication and excellence, but surrender the fruits to God without craving the results.", valueTag: 'Right Conduct', difficulty: 'Master' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan say about the importance of self-enquiry (Atma Vichara)?", options: ["Regular self-enquiry — 'Who am I?' — leads to Self-realisation", "Self-analysis is not spiritually productive", "Only qualified teachers can perform self-enquiry", "Self-enquiry creates depression and should be avoided"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan endorsed the practice of Atma Vichara — asking 'Who am I?' beneath all identifications. When one persists in this inquiry, the false identification with body-mind dissolves.", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Master' },
    { questionText: "What is the connection between Sathya Sai Baba and Prema Sai?", options: ["Bhagawan prophesied that He would reincarnate as Prema Sai Baba eight years after His passing", "Prema Sai is a different Avatar with no connection to Sathya Sai", "Prema Sai lived before Sathya Sai", "Prema Sai and Sathya Sai are concurrent Avatars"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan prophesied: The Sai Avatar comes in three forms — Shirdi Sai (Shiva), Sathya Sai (Shiva-Shakti), and Prema Sai (Shakti) — to appear in Karnataka approximately eight years after His passing.", valueTag: 'Truth', difficulty: 'Master' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan say about the relationship between all living beings?", options: ["All beings share the same Atma — to harm any creature is to harm God and yourself", "Humans are superior to animals in all respects", "Plants and animals have no spiritual significance", "Only humans have a relationship with God"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan: 'The same Atma dwells in all beings — from the tiniest insect to the mightiest elephant to the most learned scholar. Love all, for in all, God dwells.' This is the basis of Ahimsa.", valueTag: 'Non-violence', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What is the Sai teaching on managing desire?", options: ["Reduce desires gradually through wisdom and contentment — not brutal suppression", "Suppress all desires immediately through will power", "Fulfil all desires to be free of them", "Desires are natural and need not be addressed"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan: 'Reduce desires one by one. Do not try to cut them all at once — that causes stress. Gradually cultivate contentment (Santosh) and the desires naturally reduce and fall away.'", valueTag: 'Right Conduct', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    { questionText: "What does Bhagawan mean by 'Love is My form'?", options: ["God's very nature and substance is unconditional love", "Love is just one of God's many qualities", "Love is a human emotion projected onto God", "God feels love but also wrath and judgment"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan declared: 'Love is My form, Truth is My breath, Bliss is My food. My life is My message, Love is My message.' God is not merely loving — Love is what God IS.", valueTag: 'Love', difficulty: 'Seeker' },
    { questionText: "What is the Sai teaching on forgiveness?", options: ["Forgiveness is divine strength — it frees the forgiver from the prison of resentment", "Forgiveness is weakness and allows wrongdoing", "Forgiveness should be conditional on genuine apology", "Karma ensures wrongdoers will be punished — forgiveness is not required"], correctIndex: 0, explanation: "Bhagawan: 'Forgiveness is the greatest power. When you forgive, you free yourself from the chain of resentment and anger. Forgiveness is a gift you give to yourself.' It is divine strength.", valueTag: 'Love', difficulty: 'Scholar' },
    ]
